recordings.rmk: About 8 seconds was cut from the original recording to remove human/equipment noise (hand-held microphone for 10 minutes). Three species were in foreground and therefore loud (Eastern Meadowlark, Bobolink, and Savannah Sparrow). The American Crows were apparently mobbing a Great Horned Owl pair in the distance; the owls can be heard, first the male at 5:18, 5:31, 5:44, and 5:54; then the female at 6:44 and 6:45; finally chitter at 7:56. The Ring-necked Pheasant is heard shortly after 5:00. Habitat was a large shortgrass meadow (possibly fallow agricultural land) with a few shrubs and trees, bordered by mixed conifer/deciduous forest on two sides, a farm on one side, and the county road on the fourth side. Recording was made from the side of the road facing the meadow starting at 4:50 a.m. This dawn recording was the only one that picked up owl calls. The reason for doing the recording at this hour at this place was having recorded on the previous day what seemed to be Northern Bobwhite calls. It turns out that one of the Bobolinks does a fairly good imitation of the Bobwhite call, and no Northern Bobwhite was in the field, at least at this time. Temperature about 50 degrees, clear, and sun rose without haze. Wind about 5 mph.

recordings.rmk: This recording was made between two freshwater impoundments on the edge of the brackish Wilmington River. Both ponds are surrounded by vegetation which provides ideal habitat for some of the 200 species documented at this location on Skidaway Island, Chatham County, Georgia.  I used a matched pair of the Sennheiser MKH 8020s in a head-spaced array, and recorded it on a Sound Devices 722. It worked, when peak normalized to -03, but in truth I was trying to take in too much space and needed to be closer to my subject (surprise!).  I have identified 10 species, (there are more) including; Northern Cardinal, Red-winged Blackbird, Northern Parula, Pine Warbler, Yellow-throated Warbler, Common Gallinule, one or both night-herons, Red-bellied and Pileated Woodpeckers, and a prominent song which escapes me, but sounds like a newly minted adult Painted Bunting.

This is a recording of the dawn chorus at Holly Shelter Game Land on the Coastal Plain of North Carolina. Standing on a raised road embankment, I held out my iPhone at arms length toward a longleaf pine forest pocosin. Conditions were calm, and the temperature was cool. The sun hadn't yet risen, but it was twilight. 

Here is my list so far:
Carolina Wren - Song
Yellow-throated Warbler - Song
Fish Crow - Call
Eastern Towhee - Song and Call
Field Sparrow - Call
Great Crested Flycatcher - Song
Common Yellowthroat - Song

recordings.rmk: I believe I’ve figured this one out. These notes ( 0:19.0 ) should be the “chit” calls of the House Wren (compare to XC390110  ). The “dzik” calls ( 0:25.0 ) are from a Bewick’s Wren (compare to XC629169  at 55 seconds). I thought the chatter ( 0:31.2 ) might also be the House Wren, but it sounds much more like the Streak-backed Oriole, a rarity present at the time (compare to XC630420 ). In addition the first note (easier to hear when watching spectrogram play) here ( 0:31.2 ) is likely the House Wren and is quite different compared to the chatter: this would likely not be the case if the chatter belonged to the House Wren. I poured over Streak-backed Oriole recordings and found nothing that matched as well as the two wrens for the other sounds.  (Sennheiser ME62 omni mic, 24 inch Roché parabola, Marantz PMD 661).

The eBird checklist is https://ebird.org/checklist/S71724327

Thanks for your help!

Tom Barnwell

recordings.rmk:
This was recorded about 90 minutes before sunset in a mountain deciduous forest adjacent to an open area.  Most of the leaves were just coming out.  

Vocalizations by the barred owl were natural.  This is a species well known to vocalize during the day.

The sounds made by the sapsuckers were drumming (apparently territorial).  I later saw two of the birds in flight.

My original goal was to record wood thrushes but so many other species were vocalizing that I entered this as a soundscape instead.

Equipment: Olympus LS-10 equipped with a Sennheiser ME67 microphone.

Modifications to the file: cropped.
